I think the second half of the movie was alright. The first half was an utter WTF train as they jump from plot point to plot point struggling to cram two movies worth of setup into one. But it's nice that the Plageuis theory was sort of confirmed; every Sith since at least the rule of two has seemingly been the result of apprentices being possessed and mergin with the spirits of their master after defeating them; including the Sheev Palpatine we knew and loved.


I also liked how it was clear that Palpatine had a large range of "acceptable outcomes" for his plan;


Option A. Kylo kills Rey, strikes down Palpatine in anger, and Palpatine's spirit possessed Kylo and rules the galaxy as the Darth Vader that could have been if Anakin hadn't been chopped to pieces by Obi Wan.


Option B. Rey falls to the dark side and strikes down Palpatine in anger, Palpatine's spirit posseses her and rules the galaxy as Empress Palpatine. Adding insult to injury, the Skwalker lineage is wiped out, and his own descendant is Queen Bitch of the Universe.


Option C: Rey succeeds in turning Kylo to the Light or he in turning her to the Dark, and they join forces to destroy him: Palps drains their lifeforce and the power of their force bond to restore himself to life, and rules the galaxy in his own body.


This even kind of adds something to RoTJ and RoTS; Palps didn't seem to seem to mind the idea of Vader turning on him and killing him in RoTS when Vader was still whole, and I presume he wanted to turn Luke to the dark side so he could eventually take over Luke's body.



Too bad they decided to have two completely separate creative teams working on the sequel trilogy, and that's not to knock on either JJ or Rian. I'd actually have also loved to see a sequel trilogy done entirely by Rian Johnson; people love to hate on him and Last Jedi, but in a vacuum it wasn't terrible, it had some cringe moments sure, and wasted Luke, but every Star Wars movie does.


TLJ was one of the strongest movies in the saga if viewed in a complete vacuum, but one of the weakest in terms of its place in the overall saga, and terrible when viewed as the second movie in a 3 part trilogy, since it wrote the plot into a corner.


Had TLJ been the first movie (and avoided the key mistake of killing Luke instead of giving him more time to make up for his failures after regaining hope), it would have made for an solid start to a "Rian Johnson" Star Wars trilogy.

I'm mainly just glad that the Skywalker saga is wrapped up as far as movies go! I can sincerely say I had a lot of fun watching this movie. There were many, many things that were ridiculous and ridiculously impossible and I feel that was what weakened it overall. I personally like it better than Ep. 1,2, 7, and 8. As a Star Wars fanatic, I will watch it over and over with enjoyment. But, I will continue to regret that our favorite galaxy and its lure are under the tight control of the Disney movie machine (with the exception of productions such as yours) and deeper, more thoughtful storylines and concepts will often wither away on the cutting room floor replaced by things that are more profitable.

I admit that I can't figure out the mindset of many fans and their sentiments pertaining to Episode 8 and connections between all the characters. I really like the RJ Luke because of his humanity (Luke is probably my favorite character) and because I think his choices were made for compassionate and thoughtful reasons (I did not find him weak at all and clearly he got out of the funk and inspired Rey to keep going.) RJ IMO smashed the otherwise repetitive stinker of a storyline that emerged from Ep.7 which was going nowhere new or interesting. And it was Disney who determined that Luke had to die in Ep. 8 (I believe). I don't see why Rey needed to be a Palpatine (he is clearly not a family man) and that connection didn't bring them any closer, but instead muddled things (Why the hell did they do that?! I can't imagine any of his descendants being good people or otherwise remaining independent of his narcissistic controlling ways). I'm glad there was limited plot involving Palpatine because I feel he's been featured enough in other movies and I don't need more about him (however his final battle with Rey was lost in too brief fashion.). I don't mind Rey calling herself a Skywalker since the name would otherwise not continue on and she was the raised by Skywalkers.

Overall, I'd say money has the largest influence on the fates of the Star Wars and its stories. I think Ep.9 was scaled back and sped up to fit into the run time (How in the world could Anakin otherwise not show up at least somewhere?) As a result, you get and indestructible Millenium Falcon, the Imperial fleet downed in a few shots, Knights of Ren amounting to nothing, Ben Solo thrown down a hole, and Palpatine losing too quickly to Rey.

I liked how they gave us lots of "candy" or fun Star Wars action and they ended the saga in a place that seems good.

I'm loving the Mandalorian and I loved the stand-alone movies. I think they have great feel and many elements of storytelling that draw me in. I Love how these characters seem to be able to develop independently instead of being tied back so tightly into the greater story web or because of the expectations of the fans. I also imagine the financial stakes are not nearly so high and therefore depth and creativity are not nearly so constrained.

The Dark side represents the active principle of life.
The Light side represents the passive principle of life.
They are both necessary for the continuation of each other.
We need to be awake, aware, and active in order to gather our food, water, and build things to survive and then to thrive.
We need to rest, digest and sleep in order to repair ourselves from the damage caused to ourselves during our active, daytime activities.
Too much active principle and not enough passive principle, and you destroy yourself pretty quickly.
Too much passive principle and not enough active principle, and people don’t get the help that they need in terms of resources and assistance.
However, it all boils down to one thing, Death.
To conquer Death is what we’re all seeking, subconsciously.

Disappointing dishonest review, but I also understand why. The Disney era is so bad, it breaks the universe so bad, all of it is now non-canon. TROS has some of the WORST universe and character destroying elements, it even tries to completely burn down the entire OT and PT, it's unforgivable. I've been watching this channel since before TLJ but now I see, Star Wars Theory is no longer reliable, I understand now that if he admits Star Wars is dead, so is this channel and his job. So now he has to ignore the truth about them. I think he really hoped TROS would save the franchise, but now since it didn't, he has to pretend it's good because if he admits that Star Wars fans have to completely de-canonize the Disney era, that leaves him out of a job. That sucks for you, but that's just life I'm afraid, many of us have jobs that are subject circumstances beyond our control.

It's been a good ride. Star Wars lasted 35 years, which is actually really impressive. But it ended the day Lucas signed it over to the white slavers, aka Disney.

And no, George is not happy about this film or any of it, he is torn up. He was deceived and tricked into selling, and Star Wars is dead now. But we can still watch the old stuff, the OT, the PT and Clone Wars, all six seasons (I don't trust Disney with the new 7th season). I think I might finally read that Thrawn trilogy everyone talks about. It's more canon than this Disney garbage.
